The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, March 17, 2004 				 ALF halts loans ahead of merger
 SRINJOY SHARMA 																								New Delhi, March 16: Ashok Leyland Finance (ALF), the Hinduja-group promoted non-banking finance company, has stopped loan disbursements until its merger with group-run IndusInd Bank, which is expected to be completed by next month.																								The merger between the two companies  with the swap ratio fixed at 9:4 in favour of the bank  has been approved by the respective governing body and is awaiting the Reserve Bank of Indias approval.																								The Chennai-based Ashok Leyland Finance was formed in 1985 for hire, purchase and lease-finance of commercial vehicles and construction equipment produced by Ashok Leyland, the flagship company of the group. IndusInd Bank was set-up in 1994 with a capital base of Rs 100 crore and currently has assets worth around Rs 10,000 crore against ALFs Rs 2,000 crore.																								Advances for purchase of commercial vehicles would resume after the merger process has been completed, sources said, adding the firm has also postponed its plans of raising additional capital worth Rs 105 crore. In the post-merger entity, the ALF unit would be the banks retail banking unit specialising in finance of commercial vehicles, they added.																								Analysts said the merger would increase the banks network to 222 branches from 56 at present, and help in raising low-cost deposits as the non-banking finance units majority branches are spread across urban and semi-urban areas of the country. 
